The '''African Continental Free Trade Agreement''' ('''AfCFTA''') is a [[trade agreement]] between 49 [[African Union]] member states<ref name=AUJun2018SummitPressRelease>{{cite web|url=https://au.int/en/pressreleases/20180706/summary-key-decisions-and-declarations-31st-african-union-summit|title=Summary of the key decisions and declarations of the 31st African Union Summit|date=2018-06-06}}</ref><ref> {{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-43489255|title=African states agree massive trade bloc|date=2018-03-21|work=BBC News|access-date=2018-03-21|language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2018-03-21/africa-set-to-agree-3-trillion-trade-bloc-without-key-economy|title=Africa Set to Agree $3 Trillion Trade Bloc, Without Key Economy|date=2018-03-21|work=Bloomberg.com|access-date=2018-03-21|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.africanews.com/2018/03/21/forty-four-countries-sign-historic-africa-union-free-trade-agreement/|title=Forty-four countries sign historic African Union free trade agreement {{!}} Africanews|last=AfricaNews|work=Africanews|access-date=2018-03-21|language=en}}</ref>, with the goal of creating a single market followed by free movement and a single currency union.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://au.int/sites/default/files/documents/33984-doc-qa_cfta_en_rev15march.pdf|title=African Union - African Continental Free Trade Area|last=|first=|date=|website=|access-date=2018-03-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2018/03/african-continental-free-trade-area-afcfta-180317191954318.htm|title=African Continental Free Trade Area: What you need to know|last=|first=|date=|website=|access-date=2018-03-21}}{{Dead link|date=October 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>
The AfCFTA was signed in [[Kigali, Rwanda]] on 21 March 2018. Signing the Agreement does not yet establish the [[African Continental Free Trade Area]]. It will function as an umbrella to which protocols and annexes will be added. Once all documents are concluded and ratified by 22 states, the free trade area will formally exist.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.tralac.org/discussions/article/12869-how-will-the-afcfta-be-established-and-its-legal-instruments-be-implemented.html|title=How will the AfCFTA be established and its Legal Instruments be implemented?|last=Erasmus|first=Gerhard|date=22 March 2018|work=tralac Discussion|access-date=2018-03-28|publisher=trade law center|language=en-gb}}</ref>

Negotiations will continue in 2018 with Phase II, including Competition Policy, Investment and Intellectual Property Rights. A draft shall be submitted for the January 2020 AU Assembly.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://au.int/sites/default/files/decisions/34055-ext_assembly_dec_1x_e26_march.pdf|title=Decision on the draft agreement establishing the African Continental Free Trade Area (AfCFTA)|date=21 March 2018|website=au.int|publisher=African Union|access-date=}}</ref>

Kenya and Ghana were the first countries to deposit the ratification instruments on 10th May 2018 after ratification through their parliaments.<ref name=FirstRatificationsKenyaGhana>{{Cite web|url=https://au.int/en/newsevents/20180510/kenya-and-ghana-ratify-instruments-african-continental-free-trade-area|title=Kenya and Ghana to ratify instruments of African Continental Free Trade Area {{!}} African Union|website=au.int|language=en|access-date=2018-05-11}}</ref>

